  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq-list">
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">What size slow cooker do I need?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">For 1-2 people, a 3-4 quart slow cooker is usually sufficient. A 6-quart model is perfect for families of 4-5 or for batch cooking, while an 8-quart model is ideal for large gatherings or cooking whole cuts of meat.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Can I leave my slow cooker on while I am at work?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Yes, modern slow cookers are designed to be left unattended for extended periods. Programmable models are especially useful as they can automatically switch to a 'Keep Warm' setting once cooking is complete.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Do I need to brown meat before putting it in a slow cooker?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">While not strictly required for food safety, browning meat before slow cooking adds significant depth of flavor through the Maillard reaction. Some premium multi-cookers offer a built-in sear function for this.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">What is the difference between High and Low settings?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Both settings eventually reach the same simmer point (around 209°F), but High gets there much faster. Typically, 1 hour on High is equivalent to about 2-2.5 hours on Low. Low is generally preferred for tougher cuts of meat.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Are slow cooker inserts dishwasher safe?</div>
